1. Why is JavaScript called dynamically typed?

A language is called dynamically typed when the type of a variable is determined at runtime, not at compile time.

In Java, you must specify the type:

int x = 10;
x = "Hello"; // Compile-time error

In JavaScript:

let x = 10;       // number
x = "Hello";      // string
x = true;         // boolean

Here, the variable x itself has no fixed type. Only the value has a type.

Important clarification

Many beginners think:

"Variables have data types."

In JavaScript, that's not true.

Correct statement:

Values have types, variables don't.

2. Difference between primitive and non-primitive data types
Primitive	Non-Primitive
Stored by value	Stored by reference
Immutable	Mutable
Fixed size	Dynamic size
Mostly stack	Heap
Independent copy	Shared reference
Primitive
let a = 10;
let b = a;

b = 20;

console.log(a); // 10

Memory:

a → 10
b → 20
Non-Primitive
let a = {age:20};
let b = a;

b.age = 30;

console.log(a.age); // 30

Memory:

a ----+
      |
b ----+----> {age:30}

Both variables point to the same object.

3. Why does typeof null return "object"?
typeof null

Output:

"object"

This is a historical bug from the first JavaScript implementation in 1995.

Internally, values had binary tags:

000 → object

The internal representation of null accidentally received the same tag.

Since millions of websites depended on this behavior, it could never be fixed.

So:

null instanceof Object

Output:

false

Thus:

null is NOT an object. typeof null === "object" is simply a legacy bug.

4. Explain stack and heap memory

JavaScript memory is broadly divided into:

Memory
   |
   +--- Stack
   |
   +--- Heap
Stack

Stores:

Primitive values
References
Function calls
Execution contexts

Example:

let x = 10;
STACK

x → 10
Heap

Stores:

Objects
Arrays
Functions

Example:

let person = {
    name:"Piyush"
};
STACK                 HEAP

person --------> {name:"Piyush"}
Easy rule

Stack stores "where".

Heap stores "what".

5. Explain shallow copy and deep copy
Shallow Copy

Copies only the first level.

let obj1 = {
    name:"Piyush",
    address:{
        city:"Jaipur"
    }
};

let obj2 = {...obj1};

Memory:

obj1.address ----+
                 |
obj2.address ----+

So:

obj2.address.city = "Delhi";

console.log(obj1.address.city);

Output:

Delhi
Deep Copy

Creates entirely separate objects.

let obj2 =
structuredClone(obj1);

Now:

obj1.address ---> Object1
obj2.address ---> Object2

Modification doesn't affect the original.

6. What is garbage collection?

Garbage collection is the process of:

Automatically removing unused objects from memory.

Example:

let user = {
    name:"Piyush"
};

user = null;

Now nobody references the object.

So JavaScript removes it automatically.

Without garbage collection:

Memory usage
↑
↑
↑
↑
Never decreases
7. Explain Mark-and-Sweep algorithm

JavaScript engines use the Mark-and-Sweep algorithm.

Suppose:

let a = {};
let b = {};

a.ref = b;
b.ref = a;

Later:

a = null;
b = null;

Algorithm:

Step 1: Mark

Start from root objects:

window
global
current execution

Mark everything reachable.

Step 2: Sweep

Remove everything unmarked.

Example:

Reachable:
   ✓ object1
   ✓ object2

Unreachable:
   ✗ object3
   ✗ object4

Delete all unreachable objects.

8. Is JavaScript pass by reference?

This is one of the biggest interview traps.

People say:

Objects are pass by reference.

This is technically incorrect.

JavaScript is:

Always pass by value.

Example:

let obj = {age:20};

function test(x){
    x.age = 30;
}

test(obj);

What gets copied?

obj ---> address 1000

x ----> address 1000

The value copied is the address itself.

Hence:

JavaScript uses pass-by-value of references.

9. Why are Symbols always unique?
let a = Symbol("id");
let b = Symbol("id");

console.log(a === b);

Output:

false

Because Symbol was designed to create guaranteed unique identifiers.

Internally:

Symbol(id) → #101
Symbol(id) → #102

Even if descriptions match, identities differ.

This avoids property name collisions.

Example:

const ID = Symbol();

obj[ID] = 100;

Nobody can accidentally overwrite it.

10. Explain memory leaks

A memory leak happens when:

Memory is still referenced even though it is no longer needed.

Example:

let cache = [];

function add(){
    cache.push(new Array(1000000));
}

Repeated calls:

add();
add();
add();

Memory keeps increasing.

Common causes:

Global variables
data = {};
Event listeners
button.addEventListener("click",fn);

Never removed.

Timers
setInterval(()=>{
},1000);

Never cleared.

Closures
function outer(){
    let huge = new Array(1000000);

    return function(){
        console.log(huge.length);
    }
}

The closure prevents garbage collection.

